<subSubSection id="C15D05FB90DC4197A6B51004EA2740C0" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="EB4D8D6EE4876A6A7C2737A6E83EBAAB" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2F51188797932062738CE4B0607E44C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Body length: male 17 mm, female 17-19 mm. The triangle of golden pile on the mesoscutum place this species in a group with 
<taxonomicName id="635310DC7B80AEF159D0719E42FC2BE0" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureoscutus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureoscutus">
<emphasis id="2DF1A6C9E19B4A2ED3D141DB988E2006" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureoscutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="14D632237DBFF51CCD33FDFD3FEFAF6B" genus="P." lsidName="P. aureus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis id="026E240A93F8EFA80F6F6B3B2C2FE9CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="93DCE41A88DD079DDDF6A18F5E699744" genus="P." lsidName="P. trilinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trilinea">
<emphasis id="FAEAFE0FD0E7AF312FCC4E5BF0204BB7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trilinea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="593D87AD870629F60FDC6391A6C3498F" genus="P." lsidName="P. trivittatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="trivittatus">
<emphasis id="9143659C4B234049B219082F9A463F41" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. trivittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="F22D1956D2599AE4C46F382149F5A41A" authority="Reemer, 2013" authorityName="Reemer" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Peradon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Peradon fenestratus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fenestratus">
<emphasis id="4FDCCDB5315F64FF168B586BE006B2E1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Peradon fenestratus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from all four of those by the erect (instead of appressed) pile on the scutellum (
<figureCitation id="4DDCBEF193EB2B8D9CAC604F34606F0A" captionStart="Figures 13–18" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figures 13 - 18. 13 - 15 Mesoscutum: 13 Peradon aureoscutus male holotype 14 P. aureus male Ecuador CNC 15 P. trivittatus male French Guiana RMNH 16 Peradon fenestratus, scutellum lateral 17, 18 Tergites 2 and 3: 17 Peradon trilinea male holotype 18 P. aureus male holotype." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures13-18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/362275" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" tableDoi="10.3897/zookeys.896.36493.figures13-18">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9EB74715F8EF08A3071743525C3E32BC" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="D869ED176C2EA85055A0218BF2A9789B" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A8DFA2BEFFC02B8410DD25998E0F04A5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Label information of the studied Brazilian specimens in the INPA collection states that these were collected in &quot;terra firme&quot; (non-flooded) forest and at a small stream (
<normalizedToken id="5DA22CC88315DD2EB69FBA8EAF8378D3" originalValue="“igarapé”">&quot;igarape&quot;</normalizedToken>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
